	<p>Natural gas is measured in therms or BTUs. A therm is a
	measurement of the amount of heat energy in natural gas, equal to 100,000 =
BTUs.
	A BTU, or British Thermal Unit, is the quantity of heat required to raise =
the=20
	temperature of one pound of water by one degree Fahrenheit. The current ch=
arge
	for natural gas from North Shore Gas=20
	is $0.5153 per therm.
	If you would like to change the rate used in the calculations above, enter=
 a new=20
	rate below.</p>

	<p>$ <input type=3D"text" name=3D"price" value=3D"0.5153" size=3D"6"> per =
therm=20
    <input type=3D"button" value=3D"Update" class=3D"siteButton primaryButt=
on"></p>
	=09
	<h3>Gas calculator - equation</h3>
	=09
	<p>Cost to operate =3D usage (hours or load) x (BTUs/100,000) x price per =
therm<br>
	OR<br>Cost to Operate =3D usage (hours or load) x therms x price per therm=
</p>
	=09
	<h3>Conversion table</h3>
	=09
	<ul>
		<li>1 BTU =3D 0.293 watt hours</li>
		<li>100,000 BTU =3D 1 therm</li>
		<li>3,413 BTU =3D 1 kilowatt hour</li>
	</ul>

